<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-696-734  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 696 734.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 25 1989 v23 n39 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AFCOM says 'lights on' for now. (Association of ComputerOperations Management attendees on automated operations)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cortese, Amy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Operations managers at the AFCOM conference on automated computeroperations mostly agree that total automation is not attainable inthe near future, but many are planning as much automation aspossible.andP;  More realistic than unmanned data centers is theconcept of unmanned shifts with human supervision of routineoperations.andP;  The main reason for automation is the desire toincrease the quality of service while reducing staff andassociated costs and the implementation of automated operationscomes about either as a necessary step for financially troubledcompanies or as the result of careful study.andP;  Most managersplanning automation maintain that staff will be reassigned ratherthan laid off.andP;  Though IBM shops are the farthest along inautomating operations, others are making strides as well.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Association of Computer Operations ManagementOperations ManagersPlanningAutomationOperations ServicesManagement of EDP.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>